1. Explain in your own words what each term means: P(c), P(d∣c) and P(c∣d). 

    In text classification, we want to decide which class ccc (like spam/ham or positive/negative) a document ddd belongs to. 
        Bayes Rule gives:
                    P(c∣d)=P(d∣c) P(c) / P(d)
    1) P(c) — Prior
        •	P(c) is the prior probability of class c.
        •	It means, before reading the document, how likely is class c?
        •	Example: if 70% training docs are negative, then  P(negative) is high. 
    
    2) P(d ∣ c) — Likelihood
        •	P(d | c) is the likelihood.
        •	It means: if the document truly belongs to class c, how likely is it that we would see this document’s words?
        •	In Naive Bayes, we compute this using word probabilities learned from documents of that class. 
    

    3) P(c ∣ d) — Posterior
        •	P(c | d) is the posterior probability.
        •	It means: after seeing the document d, how likely is it that the class is c?
        •	This is the value we care about for prediction (we pick the class with the highest posterior). 

2. Why can the denominator P(d) be ignored when comparing classes?

        P(d) is the probability of observing the document itself, and it does not depend on the class.
          •	Since P(d) is the same constant for all classes when the document is fixed, it does not change which class is largest.
          •	So we just compare:
                    P(c) × P(d ∣ c)
            and pick the class with the bigger product. 

